messages.body:
That's the key difference. In the React app, the iframe's parent is your React application. When you call `window.parent.location.reload(false)`, it reloads the entire React app, which destroys the iframe and cancels the navigation.

In the classic app, the parent was likely another ASP frameset where reloading the parent didn't destroy the child frame in the same way (or the frame structure handled it differently).

**Fix:** Replace `window.parent.location.reload(false)` with a `postMessage` to notify the React app, and let React handle any refresh logic:

In the ASP page:
```javascript
window.location.href = handleRootUrl(url);
ToggleDisabled(true);
document.all.oProgressBar.style.display = "";
window.parent.postMessage({ type: 'reload' }, '*');
```

In your React component that hosts the iframe:
```javascript
useEffect(() => {
  const handler = (event) => {
    if (event.data?.type === 'reload') {
      // handle refresh logic here if needed
    }
  };
  window.addEventListener('message', handler);
  return () => window.removeEventListener('message', handler);
}, []);
```

Or if no parent refresh is actually needed for the React app, simply remove the line:
```javascript
// window.parent.location.reload(false);
